<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF110-374-522  </DOCNO><DOCID>10 374 522.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>ACM Transactions on Database Systems  Dec 1990 v15 n4 p518(40).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Translation with optimization from relational calculus torelational algebra having aggregate functions. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nakano, Ryohei.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Relational calculus, which is declarative, is suitable for userinterface; relational algebra, which is procedural, is suitablefor data base operations.andP;  A new point of view is presented whichclassifies the method of query translation and optimization astranslation with optimization for a translation that performssimultaneous logical optimization and optimization aftertranslation where calculus expressions are translated in any wayto algebraic expressions of some level of complexity.andO;Optimization after translation is not as effective or promising astranslation with optimization.andP;  There are two parts to thetranslation method: translation of the relational calculus kerneland translation of aggregate functions.andP;  Tests show that heuristicrewriting rules have an essential part in the optimization.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AlgorithmsData Base Management SystemsQuery ProcessingData Base DesignAlgebraCalculusQuery LanguagesTheoretical ResearchNew Technique.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Translation with optimization. (chart)Symbol notation. (table)General flow of kernel translation. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>